<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: STALLONE'S CHALLENGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Daniel Cerone 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If producer David Brown can get "The Midnight Club" going, co-producer 
Sylvester Stallone will star as New York's best detective -- in a wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
"The movie will have state-of-the-art, wheelchair, hand-to-hand combat," Brown 
tells us. 
</P>
<P>
"It's about a New York police detective determined to extinguish a crime 
overlord. . . . In his single-minded desire to wipe out this man, the detective 
is paralyzed from the waist down and almost killed. 
</P>
<P>
"Stallone goes from a man of intense activity to a wheelchair, and the action 
continues from the wheelchair." 
</P>
<P>
The script, by John Herzfeld, is based on a book by James B. Patterson, former 
CEO of the J. Walter Thompson USA ad agency. The movie, to be financed by 
Stallone's Carolco Pictures as a Tri-Star release, is expected to start 
shooting early next year. First up for Stallone: the comedy "Oscar," which 
begins shooting this fall. Daniel Cerone 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
