</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
Q &amp; A 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q: Please let me know what Wall Street thinks about Union Carbide Corp. What is 
the present health of the corporation now that the accident in Bhopal, India, 
is behind it? -- Allentown, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
A: You can always get information on the record from analysts who follow a 
company. But sometimes it is the off-the-record stuff that's more intriguing. 
</P>
<P>
One Wall Street source, who is very familiar with Carbide, says he doesn't 
expect much of an improvement in the company's earnings, mainly because its 
commodity chemical business is suffering along with the rest of that industry. 
And he doesn't expect an internal restructuring that could unlock some of the 
company's value. In short, says this source, "the management continues to screw 
up." He thinks that the stock could be worth more than $40 if a restructuring 
took place. It was selling at around $20 last week. 
</P>
<P>
The only hope for shareholders may be an unfriendly takeover attempt. And since 
junk bond, bust-up takeover bids by corporate raiders seem to be a thing of the 
past, the only potential buyer would be another chemical company or maybe an 
oil company. "Oil and chemical companies are the natural buyers, but they don't 
make unfriendly offers. And this would have to be unfriendly -- management 
likes its job," says my shy source. 
</P>
<P>
There are some admirers of Carbide, as the Wall Street Journal pointed out a 
few weeks ago. But for the most part, experts see a company whose earnings are 
slipping because of bad business conditions and because it is still paying off 
the restructuring it undertook a few years ago to escape a takeover attempt by 
GAF Corp. 
</P>
<P>
Fred Seimer, a long-time chemical analyst now with Chemical Research Corp., 
expects Carbide's earnings to fall sharply to around $2.35 a share this year 
and down again in 1991 to around $2 a share. Carbide earned $4.07 a share in 
1989, even after a big extraordinary charge. 
</P>
<P>
Seimer is one of the more pessimistic analysts. According to Institutional 
Brokers Estimate System, the average estimate of all analysts who follow 
Carbide is for earnings of $2.67 a share this year. The most optimistic analyst 
thinks that earnings could be $3.80; the most dour prediction is $2.09. 
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for the stock all depends on a restructuring," says Seimer, 
echoing my off-the-record source. "Everyone is expecting that, at some point, 
(Carbide) will restructure itself." 
</P>
<P>
Seimer says the company might decide to sell its carbon products business and 
might spin off its industrial gases operation to shareholders. When? Probably 
not this year -- the company needs the cash that these businesses generate 
right now, Seimer says. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I have made several attempts to check the status of certain savings and loan 
institutions in my area, with no success. I started with my senator and was 
given the phone number of a regulatory office in San Francisco. This office 
interrogated me as to my need for the information. 
</P>
<P>
I explained that I was investing in jumbo certificates of deposit and wanted to 
be sure that I was not putting the money in an S&amp;L that was in danger of 
being taken over. They told me that they could not give me the information I 
wanted. 
</P>
<P>
Do you know if such information is available? Is it being kept secret? -- 
Malibu, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
A: Information as to which S&amp;Ls are in trouble certainly is being kept 
secret. If it weren't, there would probably be a run on all the unhealthy 
savings institutions in the nation, and the federal government would have an 
even bigger mess to clean up. 
</P>
<P>
The federal Office of Thrift Supervision, of course, has a list of all the 
nation's troubled S&amp;Ls. I asked a spokesperson whether the government would 
like to share that information with my readers. "Heck, no," was the reply, 
"because that would make them go under. And they are doing a good job at that 
themselves." 
</P>
<P>
But there is hope. Keefe, Bruyette &amp; Woods Inc., a Wall Street investment 
firm, keeps very close tabs on the nation's banking and savings industry. The 
firm recently issued a major report on California thrifts. It also does reports 
on banks and S&amp;Ls in other regions. The firm has an office in San Francisco 
at (415) 434-3390. 
</P>
<P>
But the long and short of Keefe Bruyette's advice is: Put your money into one 
of three large California thrifts if you don't want to be troubled by a 
takeover. The firm considers Great Western Financial, Golden West Financial and 
H. F. Ahmanson &amp; Co. safe. 
</P>
<P>
But keep in mind that your deposits are insured up to $100,000, even if a 
thrift institution does get into trouble. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I would like to know if a bond I have, drawn by the state of North Carolina 
and dated 1868, has a value as a bond rather than as a collector's item. -- 
Dunkirk, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
A: The bond appears to be worthless, according to Everett Chalk, assistant 
director of North Carolina's division of state finance. Here's why. 
</P>
<P>
When the American Civil War ended in 1865, carpetbaggers traveled south to make 
their fortunes. In many instances, Chalk says, they floated bond issues for 
projects that were never really intended to be built. It took an amendment to 
the Constitution, but the carpetbaggers' debt was generally repudiated by the 
Southern states, although some did pay off bonds at far less than their face 
value. 
</P>
<P>
Chalk says the bonds that you hold do not show up on his list of North Carolina 
securities that are redeemable. But he suggests that you write to him at the 
Department of the Treasury, 325 N. Salisbury St., Raleigh, N.C. 27603, for more 
information. 
</P>
<P>
Q: My dad passed away recently and my mother found in his belongings shares of 
stock in a company called Cheyenne Resources Inc., dated Sept. 10, 1981. She 
would like to know if the company still exists. I've searched the public 
library, and looked through financial books and papers, but could not find any 
listing. -- Sarasota, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
A: Cheyenne Resources does exist, but just barely. 
</P>
<P>
According to Robert Fisher of R. M. Smythe &amp; Co., the New York company that 
specializes in finding long-lost companies, "Cheyenne was incorporated under 
the laws of Wyoming and is still in existence." Its address is 3001 Henderson 
Drive, Suite A, Cheyenne, Wyo. 82001, (307) 632-6437. 
</P>
<P>
Fisher says Cheyenne's stock trades over- the-counter and is now offered at 
only 1 cent a share, with no bids. "In the absence of a bid for the stock, it 
is doubtful whether any value will accrue to this holding," Fisher says. JOHN 
CRUDELE 
</P>
</TEXT>
