<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 1; Column 1; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1182 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA TRENDS: RISE IN HOMEOWNER ASSOCIATION WOES PROMPTS STATE ACTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRADLEY INMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Sheila Newsome closes escrow on her new house in Long Beach this month, 
she will also purchase a stake in a corporation that can be held liable for her 
personal safety, that can foreclose on her property and that can tell her what 
color her new home can be painted. 
</P>
<P>
Newsome is a new homeowner and also a first-time member of a residential 
community association, a legal entity that manages and polices the affairs of 
her development and yields consider able clout over how people live together. 
</P>
<P>
The growing influence of community associations in California has prompted the 
state Legislature to convene the Select Committee on Common Interest 
Subdivisions, chaired by Assemblyman Dan Hawser (D-Arcata). Among other things, 
the special committee is expected to consider whether a proliferation of 
lawsuits and community association-related complaints justifies establishing a 
state agency to regulate associations. The committee will hold hearings 
beginning July 31. 
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 3 million Californians belong to residential 
community associations, with nearly half located in single-family subdivisions. 
They represent a radical transformation in the ownership of private property in 
the state and have revolutionized how our communities are governed. 
</P>
<P>
Once a new residential development is completed, associations are legally 
organized as mutual benefit corporations. With a volunteer board of directors 
and a paid staff or professional management firm, they collect dues and 
maintain common areas, such as open space, streets, swimming pools, corridors 
and playgrounds. Associations also enforce the property's covenants and deed 
restrictions, which may include rules on loud music, design standards and how a 
lawn must be landscaped. 
</P>
<P>
Home buyers automatically become members of the association and must abide by 
the rules. When a homeowner consistently violates the bylaws, such as 
nonpayment of dues, an association can place a lien on the property and even 
execute foreclosure proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
"People think that they know what owning a house is all about, but they don't, 
because this is a radical departure from ownership as we have known it in the 
past," said UC Berkeley research associate Carol Silverman. 
</P>
<P>
Expensive and complex legal brawls and consumer complaints have prompted the 
Legislature to look into community associations. 
</P>
<P>
San Francisco homeowner Suzanne Sarra's gripe is a familiar one. She lives in a 
small condominium complex where a lawsuit between her homeowners association 
and the developer has held up home sales and hurt property values. 
</P>
<P>
"This has been a very frustrating experience; we are a small association 
without a lot of reliable information," she said. "There should be some sort of 
government agency to help. We didn't know what to do, so we hired an attorney, 
which hasn't been cheap." 
</P>
<P>
The number of appellate court decisions related to community associations 
tripled between 1988 and 1989, according professor Katharine Rosenberry of the 
California Western School of Law in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
"Phase 1 in the evolution (of community associations) is building all of these 
projects and getting people to live in them," Rosenberry said. "And now for 
Phase 2, when neighbors must learn to live with another and they begin to 
disagree and they begin to sue." 
</P>
<P>
The proliferation of associations accounts for the increased number of 
conflicts that have come to the attention of the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
In California, 18,000 subdivisions and townhome and condominium projects have 
associations with collective operating budgets that exceed $1 billion. It is 
estimated that 70% of all new for-sale developments in the state that have more 
than four units are organized with community associations. 
</P>
<P>
Residential associations date back to 1743, when the Earl of Leicester 
constructed townhomes surrounding a public square. Residents set up a legal 
device to maintain the area so that they could have exclusive use of the 
square. 
</P>
<P>
After World War I, residential associations in the United States were used to 
enforce restrictive covenants that prohibited racial minorities. 
</P>
<P>
In California, the first community association was founded in 1912 when the St. 
Francis Wood single-family subdivision was built in San Francisco. But it 
wasn't until after the passage of Proposition 13 in 1978 that the number of 
associations mushroomed. 
</P>
<P>
Before that, community associations governed fewer than 200 developments 
throughout the state, and the vast majority of those were upscale condominiums 
and townhome developments. 
</P>
<P>
"The fiscal problems of local government following the enact ment of 
Proposition 13 accelerated the use of associations," according Silverman. "By 
requiring the developer to provide streets, street lighting, visitor parking, 
water and sewer lines, parks and playgrounds, localities can minimize the 
fiscal impact of new development," Silverman said. 
</P>
<P>
Once these common amenities are built, the developer sets up a community 
association to maintain them. Not only have associations assumed 
responsibilities traditionally provided by local government, but they tackle 
broader duties. 
</P>
<P>
For example, an association has unique responsibilities to safeguard its 
residents. In the California Supreme Court case of Frances T. vs. the Village 
Green Owners Assn., a Los Angeles woman won a lawsuit against a homeowners 
association because it failed to provide adequate outdoor lighting that might 
have prevented the woman's rape. 
</P>
<P>
"A city doesn't have the (legal) responsibility to protect you against crime, 
but here we have a case that says a homeowners association can be held 
negligent for the same thing," Rosenberry said. 
</P>
<P>
In other instances, associations have become a crutch for solving neighborhood 
spats. 
</P>
<P>
"Before we had associations policing illegally parked cars and shoddy 
landscaping, these problems were worked out neighbor to neighbor," Rosenberry 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, some experts say it is time to establish a consumer-oriented 
regulatory agency to protect homeowners from abuses and to offer information 
and redress for people who feel victimized by community associations or 
developers. 
</P>
<P>
"After the developer completes the project, there is no regulatory oversight," 
Silverman said. "It makes sense to have an agency that would protect the 
consumer." 
</P>
<P>
The California Department of Real Estate works with the developer to set up the 
association, but the state agency washes its hands after it is established. 
</P>
<P>
Silverman points to the Bureau of Condominiums in Florida, which is a 
government regulatory body funded by fees from developers and homeowners. Such 
an agency can offer mediation services in legal disputes, oversee the election 
of association officers, require the licensing of association property managers 
and provide consumer education. 
</P>
<P>
"If it's set up to offer the homeowner better information and to regulate the 
people that are hired to run these organizations, then it's a good idea," 
Rosenberry said. "But if it's set up to resolve disputes over barking dogs, it 
will be a waste of taxpayers' money." 
</P>
</TEXT>
