<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER NOTEBOOK: IT'S IMPORTANT TO RECORD REAL ESTATE DEALS; 
</P>
<P>
DOCUMENTS: FOLLOWING THE PROPER PROCEDURES CAN PROTECT AN OWNER FROM FINANCIAL 
LOSS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT J. BRUSS, Bruss is a San Francisco-based syndicated real estate 
columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A surprisingly large number of real estate documents remain unrecorded, usually 
due to ignorance. Failure to record a deed, mortgage or other realty document 
can cause unnecessary but often huge financial losses. 
</P>
<P>
For example, home buyers sometimes don't record their deeds for fear the lender 
will call the low interest rate mortgage if it is not assumable, the property 
will be reassessed to raise the property tax, or that a pre-existing judgment 
or income tax lien will attach to the property. 
</P>
<P>
These may seem like valid reasons for not recording a deed, but the buyer 
should be aware (1) an unscrupulous seller might sell the same property to 
another buyer who records his deed first, (2) the seller could incur income tax 
or judgment liens that will attach to the property, or worse yet, (3) the 
seller might file bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
When a lender such as a home seller who is helping to finance the sale receives 
a mortgage and fails to record the deed, the lender could only look to the 
borrower and not to the property for repayment. 
</P>
<P>
Documents are recorded with the county recorder of deeds to give constructive 
notice of the contents of the documents. Any person dealing with real estate is 
presumed to know of the recorded papers affecting a specific property, such as 
deeds, mortgages, liens and judgments. 
</P>
<P>
By searching the public records, anyone can determine who owns a property and 
what liens or other encumbrances affect the title. Many counties now have 
computerized records. 
</P>
<P>
The basic recording rule is "first in time is first in right." This means that 
the first recorded document has priority over a later recorded document, even 
if the second document to be recorded was executed earlier than the first 
document recorded. 
</P>
<P>
This priority of recording can be very critical. Suppose you loan a homeowner 
$10,000 secured by what you thought would be a second mortgage on the house. 
But the homeowner then borrows $20,000 from another lender, who immediately 
records his mortgage before you record yours. The $20,000 lender would have a 
second mortgage and because you delayed recording, you would have a third 
mortgage securing your $10,000 loan. Even a one-minute difference can be 
critical to determining the priority of a mortgage. 
</P>
<P>
Virtually any document affecting real estate is eligible for recording if it is 
properly notarized. Deeds, mortgages, trust deeds, leases, purchase options, 
land contracts and purchase agreements are a few examples of documents eligible 
for recording. My neighbor and I recently signed a notarized "fence agreement," 
which she can record. 
</P>
<P>
But improper recording of a document against a property creates a "title 
cloud," which may give rise to a lawsuit for damages due to "slander of title," 
a serious offense. For example, if a mortgage lender mistakenly records a 
mortgage against your house instead of the one next door, that would be slander 
of your title. 
</P>
<P>
An unusual type of recordable document is a lis pendens, which is recorded 
against a property when litigation involving its title has been filed. The lis 
pendens simply warns any buyer or lender that the property title is in 
litigation and that anyone dealing with the property does so subject to the 
outcome of the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
"Wild documents" are recorded documents that usually contain an error, thus 
placing them outside the chain of title. For example, suppose Smith owns a 
property but buyer Jones records a deed to him from seller Thompson. This is a 
wild document because no deed was recorded from Smith to Thompson. Although 
such a deed from Smith to Thompson may exist, if it was not recorded, it gave 
no constructive notice, so the deed to Smith is a wild document outside the 
chain of title. 
</P>
<P>
Most property buyers and sellers don't worry about the recording laws. Whenever 
they acquire a property, they make certain they receive an owner's title 
insurance policy. Then if there is a recording error, the title insurer will 
pay for correcting the problem. 
</P>
<P>
Without title insurance, property titles would be in chaos. Especially when 
acquiring property from friends and relatives, title insurance is vital to be 
certain there are no unexpected liens or encumbrances. Not only does title 
insurance insure the document as it was represented, but unexpected title risks 
such as forged signatures, rights of ex-spouses, claims by missing heirs, title 
claims by minors and incompetent persons, and improperly recorded instruments 
also are insured. Further information on recording laws is available from a 
local real estate attorney or title insurance officer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
