<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOARD PROVIDES RESEARCH ON PROPERTIES TO BUYERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state Structural Pest Control Board regulates pest control operators and 
requires that copies of inspection reports and work completion notices be filed 
with its office. 
</P>
<P>
If home buyers want to research a property, the reports and notices for the 
last two years on any address are available for a $2 search fee. 
</P>
<P>
The pest control board will also tell consumers the number of settled 
complaints an exterminator has had in the last two years, but can't discuss 
pending complaints. 
</P>
<P>
Consumers can file complaints about inspections or treatments for up to two 
years afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
Although it's typical for sellers to take care of termite work, a lot of 
complaints occur after buyers allow the seller and real estate agents to handle 
it, said Maureen Sharp, deputy registrar. After buyers move in, they are 
dissatisfied with the work and complain. The board recommends that buyers order 
their own termite inspections and consider getting two or three to compare 
findings. 
</P>
<P>
It also suggests getting referrals from satisfied customers when choosing an 
exterminator. 
</P>
<P>
Call the pest control board at (213) 620-2255 or (916) 920-6323 for more 
information, or send inquiries to 1430 Howe Ave., Sacramento, Calif. 95825. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072290-0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 250981 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 22, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
