<P>
</P>
<P>
Drugs and Driver's Licenses 
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 331 to 88, the House adopted an amendment inducing states to 
suspend the driver's licenses of drug criminals. States not doing so would lose 
2% of their federal highway funds. The amendment was attached to a fiscal 1991 
transportation appropriations bill (HR 5229). 
</P>
<P>
Supporter Gene Taylor (D-Miss.) said, "At times we have to forget about things 
like states' rights and address the horrible drug problem in our nation." 
</P>
<P>
Opponent Tom DeLay (R-Tex.) objected to "sort of a blackmail attitude of 
withholding federal highway funds because states do not pass certain laws." 
</P>
<P>
A yes vote was for the amendment. 
